  <span id="freeText819184630226570770" style="display:none">This was the first or second John Grisham book I ever read. I read it years ago - in fact, I think when I read it the most recent Grisham book release was <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/32499.The_Pelican_Brief" title="The Pelican Brief by John Grisham" rel="nofollow noopener">The Pelican Brief</a> or maybe <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5359.The_Client" title="The Client by John Grisham" rel="nofollow noopener">The Client</a>. <br /><br />I remember enjoying this book a lot and that all of his early books had a similar feel and were very easy to get into. It was also the start of my expectation that several times throughout a Grisham you will get details on what the main characters are eating or drinking. Instead of just saying he grabbed a bite to eat on the way home, you always get details about what was ordered and usually a couple of beers are involved. When he does that in his newer releases I automatically think "Classic Grisham!"<br /><br />I have managed to read most of his books over the years, and while many are not up to the same standard as his early books, I still enjoy checking them out every time there is a new release.</span>
