  <span id="freeText17578031439875795864" style="display:none">Classic everyone is familiar with. I just want to note how refreshing it was, in this day and age, to read complex legal thriller (although basic idea is very simple), without intrusion of words like cellphone, email, Internet, hacker, alias, virus and all the complications and simplifications in plot that come with it. In this book, you have to "wait by the phone", it's absolutely crucial for things not to go bonkas. Phone boots are little tin houses of salvation. To me, that scarcity of communication possibilities, with simultaneous realistic chance to stay invisible, despite bugged cars and homes, with all the FBI an Mafia zeroed in on you ("If I hit the break pedal, I would have 10 noses up my ass"), creates special atmosphere in these narratives and movies from early nineties and before. No cctv on every corner. No phone in every pocket, or any for that matter. No drones filming your hemorrhoids from 10000 feet. So what's one left with in this book, without all the stupid gadgets and copier machine being the highest tech? Mindgames! Lots of them. And real storytelling. Which is also kind of a mindgame, I guess.</span>
