  <span id="freeText6270862138884455714" style="display:none">It's been a while I have read a John Grisham novel. And <i> The Firm </i> provided a good opportunity for me to get back the world of Grisham and his legal thrillers. And as always I'm amply rewarded.<br /><br />The Firm is undoubtedly a gripping thriller. With somewhat a slow start the story slowly but steadily picks up the pace and become a quick page turner. And from mid story onward, the suspense become intense. <br /><br />Coupled with all these thrilling features is an incredible story line. A young ambitious lawyer is approached by a small law firm with a fantastic job offer and perks that he could only dream of. He is smart but broke. So even though he had few reservations, he ultimately accepts it. Little that he knows that he signs a death deal and that soon his fantastic dream becomes his worst nightmare. I really enjoyed the story line, even though at times, it was a little far fetched. It is fresh and original in concept. The combination of mafia and a law firm that represent them is simply incredible. Who could think of that but a legal mind with a knack for thrillers? And John Grisham is the man. <br /><br />With Mitch McDeere, Grisham had created a savvy protagonist. He runs the show for which Grisham set up the perfect stage. He is perhaps too good to be true. But Mitch McDeere is one of the most bold, smart and resourceful character that I have come across in a Grisham work so far. <br /><br />Grisham's writing is simple and clean as always, but a certain audacity can be sensed overall. The dialogues were witty and humorous. I had a good laugh amidst suspense. <br /><br />Overall, I really liked this legal thriller by John Grisham. With the read of <i> The Firm,</i> I have read the first three works of his. I have read few of his other works, but to me, the first three works - <i> A Time to Kill, The Firm </i> and <i> The Pelican Brief </i> - are his best.</span>
